      "clinicalPresentation": "Gram-negative bacteremia often presents acutely: high fevers, rigors, hypotension, and rapid clinical deterioration. Source-specific presentations: urinary source — dysuria, flank pain, pyuria; intra-abdominal — abdominal pain, peritoneal signs; biliary — RUQ pain, jaundice (Charcot triad), cholangitis; pneumonia — cough, hypoxia, infiltrates; line-related — erythema/purulence at catheter site. E. coli is the most common organism, followed by Klebsiella. Pseudomonas bacteremia carries higher mortality and typically involves immunocompromised hosts or healthcare-associated sources.",
      "diagnostics": "Blood cultures (2 sets from separate sites before antibiotics), source-directed imaging (CT abdomen for intra-abdominal source, renal US or CT for urinary obstruction, biliary US for cholangitis), urinalysis and urine culture, sputum culture if respiratory symptoms. For resistant organisms: request confirmatory susceptibility testing for ESBL, AmpC, and carbapenemase production (CRE). Follow-up blood cultures at 48-72h to document clearance (less rigidly mandated than SAB, but recommended for high-risk infections — Pseudomonas, CRE, immunocompromised, or persistent fever).",
